english:
  title: Epitaph for Master Yun Mun-jeong of Yuljeong
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Three months after Master Yuljeong was laid to rest, his grandson Sojong came to me bearing the family chronicle his grandfather had composed, requesting that I inscribe the tomb with an epitaph. Alas, the Master has gone. When I fled from Beijing upon hearing of my father's passing, the Master came before the others to weep at his tomb. After the mourning was done, he grasped my hand and sighed heavily for a long time before departing. Now twenty years have passed, and I have not dared forget that day. Yet the road is long, and I could not journey to his grave to weep myself. How could I refuse to write this epitaph?

    The Master's name was Taek, and his courtesy name was Jung-deok. His great-grandfather Yangbi served as household chief of Mosong County. His grandfather Hae held the rank of Minister of Rites and was Great Keeper of the National Academy, later retiring with honor. When serving as magistrate's clerk in Sangju, a man defiled his sister. At that time, a terrible drought afflicted the land. The Minister contested with the regional governor and had the man executed with utmost severity. Thereupon Heaven sent rain. Throughout his career in the Ministry of Punishments and the Censorate, he maintained unwavering integrity and righteousness. As inspector of Gyeongsang, Jeolla, Yangguang, and Huaiyang provinces, and later as Vice Minister, he was so poor that he could not afford even porridge, subsisting on boiled beans. The world called him a man of pristine virtue and incorruptible conduct. His father Sunyeong, though passing before him, received the posthumous rank of Vice Minister. His mother, Lady Kim, bore the title of Lady of Jinye Province.

    The Master was born in the cyclical year of Gichuk under the Yuan. From his third year, he took to learning, and what he studied he could recite perfectly. Whenever his grandfather saw him utter striking phrases, the old man would weep in his arms and say, "It is you who shall restore our house! Sunyeong does not truly die!" As he matured, he became deeply committed to self-cultivation, studying under his maternal uncle Yun Seonjwa, who had once achieved the highest honor in the examinations. There was nothing he failed to master, and he became especially profound in the Spring and Autumn Annals of Zuo. He often recited the words of Fan Zhongyan: "I grieve for the world's troubles before others grieve, and I rejoice in the world's joy after others rejoice." Thus he declared, "How could a great man live an ordinary life?"

    In the year Jeongsa of the Yanyou era, he passed the civil service examination for jinshi degree. In Gyeongsin, he ranked first in the examination for the Treasure Sword essay, and his work was widely circulated and praised. He was appointed magistrate's clerk of Gyeongsan Prefecture, where he encouraged agriculture, repaired schools, and taught the people ritual propriety and filial piety, thereby flourishing customs and virtue. Entering the Bureau of Records, he served as proofreader and inspector. Though his rank was merely the ninth grade, he bore himself as a chancellor. Some called him arrogant, but he maintained his dignity without doubt.

    In the year Imsin of the Zhishun era, when the Prince of Yiling lodged in Beijing, the Master rode alone to pay his respects. The Prince saw him once and recognized at once his extraordinary worth. He spoke words of entrustment concerning the succession, his intention turning toward the present sovereign. The Master demurred, saying, "I am now old. What can I accomplish?" The following year, when the sovereign held court in Seogyeong, the Master served as Chief Inspector and Military Advisor, ensuring all preparations were orderly. The people found peace through his administration. The sovereign often sighed, "What a worthy man! Like Yan Hui himself!" This was because the Master resembled a man from the Central Plains.

    When an imperial envoy arrived bearing a proclamation, the sovereign commanded the Master to read it. The attendants objected, saying this was not customary. The sovereign replied, "Cannot the chief advisor serve in place of both the inner and outer chancellors at my discretion?" He was appointed Vice Counselor and granted the purple robe. Soon the sovereign wished to make him governor of the capital, but deeming his merit-rank too low, promoted him instead to magistrate. When someone slandered the Master as disrespectful, the sovereign declared, "Yun is a loyal man. This calumny must be yours."

    In the year Muin, he was appointed Right Vice Counselor and took charge of examinations and appointments. The sovereign wished to give his son the rank of palace guard, but the Master replied, "A position of honor is precious. Even worthy and meritorious officials remain in humble stations. Dare I accept such favor for my son?" The sovereign esteemed him all the more. In Gimyo, he advanced to Right Counselor and conducted examinations at the National Academy, selecting ninety-nine men including An Won-nyong and other renowned scholars.

    In the third lunar month of Gyemyu, the sovereign fell gravely ill. He spoke again to the Master of the words he had entrusted in Beijing. The Master knelt and replied, "The sovereign need not trouble himself." When the Prince of Yeongneung ascended, undertaking reforms, the Master retired to the countryside to preserve his health. When the Prince of Myeongneung took the throne, the Master was selected to govern Naju Province. Wherever he went, he governed with clemency, restraining the violent and uplifting the weak. When the Prince of Chongneung ascended, he was demoted to magistrate of Gwangyang.

    When the Prince of Myeongneung passed, the people's hopes turned to the present sovereign. The Master impeached a memorial to the Yuan capital, stating that in our kingdom, elder and younger brothers, uncles and nephews, succeed one another, and a young sovereign cannot bear the weight of guardianship. His words were cutting and earnest. The Prince of Chongneung harbored resentment and thus issued the demotion.

    In the year Sinmyo, when the sovereign began his rule, the Master entered the Privy Council as Chief Instructor. He resolved to right the affairs of the age, submitting memorials with proposals. When these were not approved, he retired as Governor of Gaeseong at the age of sixty-four. When courtiers proposed sending local music to Yuan as tribute, the Master submitted a memorial: "The World Emperor already rejected this. If we offer it again, shall we not invite ridicule?" He also urged frugality, and the sovereign took his counsel deeply to heart.

    When plans were made to build a palace in Nanjing, the Master remonstrated: "The monk Myocheong beguiled King Injong and nearly destroyed the nation. That calamity is no distant memory. Moreover, as we must garrison our borders against invasion and our soldiers are already stretched thin, how can we raise labor for construction without depleting our foundation?" The sovereign commanded the Book of Documents to be copied and distributed to his ministers, and ordered the Master to lecture upon it. The Master expounded how Duke of Zhou assisted King Cheng through diligence, saying, "I pray that the sovereign will emulate King Cheng, heed Duke Zhou's teachings, and govern with solemnity and deference. Thus shall the state be blessed." The sovereign received this with utmost seriousness.

    The Master also presented for court instruction Zhen Dexiu's Elucidation of the Great Learning, noting that Choi Seung-ro of our realm had similarly offered instruction to King Seongjong. At this time, the sovereign had grown enamored of Buddhist teachings and harbored thoughts of renouncing worldly life. The Master remonstrated: "The sovereign serves Heaven and the ancestral temples above, and protects the people below. How can he imitate the abandonment of righteousness by some common man? If you will heed my words, there is no way but the way of Confucius. I beseech you to consider this deeply."

    Regarding the labor at Baekak, the Master spoke forcefully against it, saying, "Though the sovereign clearly comprehends the merits and faults of all matters, when entrusted to ministers, if immediate orders are not given, time passes and the harm is already done, and remedy becomes impossible." The sovereign gave him wine. The Master drank three cups at once, his spirit unmoved and bearing unchanged. The former Vice Minister Hong Yeon-bak marveled, saying, "I did not know Counselor Yun's forthrightness reached such heights. I cannot compare."

    Though the Master had retired, remembering the sovereign's words at his deathbed, he spoke whatever he knew without reservation, sometimes with cutting directness. Yet the sovereign bore with him gently. In the year Gapjin, at the age of seventy-six, the Master fell ill and requested to return to Geumju, where he dwelt in the mountains and waters for seven years, yet his heart of devotion to the sovereign never ceased for a moment.

    In the eighth lunar month of Gyeongseul, on the day Byeongja, he called his sons and grandsons before him and instructed them: "Our grandfather Minister Jeong-heon arose from humble station and earned renown through purity and loyalty. My father, sadly, passed young, and I always feared I could not continue his legacy. Yet by the sovereign's grace, I have received honors far exceeding my desert, and I have lived beyond fourscore years. This is all the hidden virtue of my forebears, the purity that Minister Jeong-heon left behind. Keep this treasure and let it not fall. When I die, do not heed auspicious calendars. Use the Buddhist rites, but without extravagance."

    On the day Jeongyu of the ninth month, he passed from this world. That very night, a great wind and rain descended, yet ceased when the coffin was sealed. On the day Giha, he was interred beside his mother's tomb. When the tidings reached the sovereign, he grieved deeply and ordered the Grand Historian to bestow upon him the posthumous name Mun-jeong (文貞). Thus the Master received all honor in his passing without blemish.

    Having lost his father in childhood, the Master never saw his face. At seasonal offerings and tomb visits, he would weep bitterly and be overcome with sorrow. Whenever he read in chronicles of filial devotion, tears would flow and his voice would fail him. He always carried a small pouch and whenever he obtained a delicacy, he would place it within to bring home to his mother, never ceasing though others laughed. When his maternal uncle passed, his granddaughters were left without support. The Master declared, "If I do not care for my uncle's granddaughters, what kind of man am I?" He found husbands for them among worthy scholars.

    Traveling in the capital, he found a hundred pieces of gold in the road and kept them, waiting for the owner. When the owner came weeping to retrieve them, the Master returned them without any expression of having done a kindness. Throughout his life, he used coarse cotton bedding and worn mats. Sometimes he lacked for meals, yet bore it without complaint. Yet when fine days of spring and autumn came, he would always prepare wine and invite guests, indulging his nature in such ease.

    The Master took four wives: Lady Mun, daughter of the jinshi Fu, bore him his eldest son Gwi-saeng, who served as court attendant. His second wife, Lady Lee, daughter of the palace guard Chang-yeon, bore him his son Bong-saeng, who became a general. His daughter married the jinshi Kim Yo, and his second daughter married the late Chamberlain and Compiler of Edicts Heo Sik. His third wife, Lady Ki, daughter of Vice Minister Yeon, bore him his son Dong-myeong, who passed the examination and served as official of the Board of Punishments. His daughter married General Pak Gwi-ryeong. He also married another Lady Ki, daughter of the Inspector-General Jeong-bo, by whom he had a daughter who became the wife of the jinshi Yi Jon-jung.

    He had nine grandsons: Hyo-jong, a court attendant who passed the jinshi examination in Gyesa; Chang-jong, a court attendant; Sa-jong, recording clerk of Heungseun Palace; Seon-chang, who pursued Buddhist learning; Seo-jong, who became top graduate in Ulsa and served as official of the Board of Rites; Hoe-jong, Heung-jong who served as livestock officer, Moo-jong, and Su-jong. He had four granddaughters and two grandsons by marriage—Heo Cho, a National Academy student, and Pak Sul—with three granddaughters, and four great-grandsons still in their youth.

    Ah, when extraordinary talents of great worth appear, they come but rarely in the world. Whether they go unmet by their time, or meet their time but go unused, or are used but briefly—all is Heaven's will. The regard that Prince Yiling showed Master Yuljeong was a thing to occur but once in a thousand years, yet the Prince's passing came all too soon. The present sovereign also honors the Master deeply, even inscribing with his own brush the characters "Yuljeong" and presenting them as a gift. Yet the Master served in the government but months before retiring, and dwelt in seclusion for nineteen years. Though his remonstrances were earnest and direct, what could they ultimately avail?

    Alas, how sorrowful! Thus I write this epitaph:

    Majestic Mun-jeong,
    striding with righteous bearing—
    though stationed at the lowest rank,
    he bore the essence of a chancellor.
    Once the Prince beheld him,
    revealing his inmost heart,
    entrusting future care to his hands—
    truly matching his great design.

    First tested as chief advisor,
    then summoned to the capital's office,
    advanced to magistrate
    in this rare blessing from the throne.

    Controlling the sovereign's words,
    shaping the selection of talent,
    poised to govern great affairs—
    yet suddenly the gates of heaven closed.

    With loyal heart unflinching,
    first stymied, then vindicated,
    the people hoped for his rise,
    yet he bore discontent.

    What troubled him so?
    His earnest words, like bitter medicine—
    why were they not heeded?

    In Geumju's green mountains,
    beneath the dense and verdant groves,
    the spirit rises toward heaven—
    this is the Master's final rest.

    Should you doubt these words,
    look upon this engraved stone.
  footnotes:
    - Yuljeong (栗亭) refers to the Master's retirement home, literally 'Chestnut Pavilion.' The name became his principal appellation.
    - Prince Yiling (懿陵), also known as King Chunghye, died after a brief reign. His early death was a turning point in the Master's career, limiting the political influence he might otherwise have wielded.
    - The 'empty talk of Kongsang' (空桑之譚) refers to Buddhist mystical discourse, which the sovereign was drawn toward. The Master opposed this attraction, fearing it would lead the ruler away from Confucian governance.
    - The Master's refusal to recommend his own son for advancement demonstrates the Confucian principle that merit, not kinship, should determine office—a rare virtue in his era.
    - The "Book of Documents, chapter on 'Without Leisure'" (無逸篇) warns against indolence and advocates for the sovereign's diligent administration, a text the Master considered essential teaching for the throne.
